A trace N/NE breeze, Beaufort 2 but a big swell. Filling in for Tony L/MAS seawatch. Don Glasco came by for a bit. A couple of Humpback Whales early, then distant but thrilling views of a Blue Whale blowing and then shallow diving showing off its dorsal fin and back. This is only the second time I've ever seen Blues from shore.

checklist_comments: filling-in for Tony Leukering's MAS seawatch on his day off; swarms of runners on Ocean View as part of Big Sur Half-Marathon this a.m. (so I had to walk to seawatch site). Sunny, very calm, seas flat calm, tide high. Not much actual migration is the calm weather. Don Glasco present early this hour, then Mark Kudrav.

filling-in for Tony Leukering's MAS seawatch on his day off; the Big Sur Half-Marathon wound down this hour and Ocean View re-opened. Patchy clouds and sun, very calm, seas flat calm, tide high. Not much actual migration is the calm weather. Mark Kudrav was present this hour; he spotted many of these birds so there were co-counters this hour. Mark saw the Blue Whale the whale-watching boats were chasing this hour.

filling-in for Tony Leukering's MAS seawatch on his day off; the Big Sur Half-Marathon wound down this hour and Ocean View re-opened. Patchy clouds and sun, very calm, seas flat calm, tide high. Not much actual migration is the calm weather. Mark Kudrav was present this hour; he spotted many of these birds so there were co-counters this hour. filling-in for Tony Leukering's MAS seawatch on his day off. Now cloudy and muggy, still very calm, seas flat calm. Not much actual migration is the calm weather. Mark Kudrav was present this hour; he spotted many of these birds so there were co-counters this hour. Also present later in the hour were Tony Leukering and Sean Fitzgerald from AZ, and then Rita arrived, and then even later Paul Fenwick. I also saw a couple of migrant Monarchs, and a pod of 20+ Risso's Dolphin just off the red buoy

Counting solo using clipboard and pen, binocs and spotting scope. Large number of Gulls feeding on the remains of Pacific Red Crab.
Counting solo using clipboard and pen, binocs and spotting scope. Large number of Gulls feeding on the remains of Pacific Red Crab.

standing watch on MAS seawatch, with Robert Horn, Rita (who arrived mid-hour). Overcast, calm, cold, seas choppy with large swell and breakers. Formal protocol for all migrants (with clickers for loons, scoters, pelicans) but I also estimated all species (as migration was slow). Thousands of gulls feeding on pelagic red crabs were estimated; they are not migrating. Also foraging Fulmars and cormorants estimated. These may be deleted from formal MAS seawatch count.

standing watch on MAS seawatch, with Rita (she left for a short time to check Crespi). Overcast during to sun mid-hour, calm, cool, seas choppy with large swell and breakers. Formal protocol for all migrants (with clickers for loons, scoters, pelicans) but I also estimated all species. Thousands of gulls feeding on pelagic red crabs increased throughout the hour until a minimum of 4000 were estimated. Also foraging Fulmars and cormorants estimated. These may be deleted from formal MAS seawatch count.

standing watch at MAS seawatch with Tony Leukering (not "on-watch" per se, photographing and clicking pelicans) and fairly soon into the hour, Blake Matheson. Clear with a few clouds but cold (low 50s) with NW wind 8-10 mph, huge breakers and choppy seas with big swells. Using clickers for PALO, BVSH, BRPE, COMU. Remaining species tallied using Leukering protocols, with the exception that I kept track of NOFU, PECO and have added an estimate for BRCO and WEGU at end of hour. One Gray Whale close.

observation_details: *truly amazing. Clouds of birds everywhere except overhead. Some birds close to shore leaving the bay but most either cutting across the bay or bypassing it offshore. Probably missed 5k+ the first 15 or so minutes I was counting alone and hadn’t fully appreciated the offshore conveyer belt that was happening.

observation_details: *new seawatch high count. Almost all were part of an impressive ‘conveyer belt’ of birds approximately a couple miles offshore and often stacked 50 birds high and multiple lines deep. These birds were not broken into flocks but just in a constant fire hose stream. A small percentage of birds were coming out of the bay and formed a completely independent flight from the conveyer belt.

observation_details: Almost certainly an undercount. There were two dominant flightlines: one that was quite high and passing basically directly overhead the Seawatch. I started counting this flightline individually and quickly had to switch the clicker to 10s. I tallied just under 6000 loons on this high line. It was a gorgeous charismatic flight, and I am not exaggerating when I say that the few early-morning passers-by I was able to point the spectacle out to were moved religiously. However, I suspected that, with light west winds, the outer bay loon line (which does not intersect with the "high line") would be even busier. It was. I decided the best way to deal with this would be to plant the scope on one point within that line for thirty-second intervals every 4 minutes and thus calculate numbers for that flightline. The rate of loons stayed quite steady: in most 30-second intervals I recorded 110-150 loons, though I got as low as 70 in an interval and as high as 195 in an interval. The light was quite good for this part of the count, and I was able to see about as far to the west as you ever can here. Grateful for that. In the close loon flocks the composition was overwhelmingly Pacific, and I was able to pick out adult Red-throats from most reaches of the distant line.
